Similar problems:
[224. Basic Calculator](https://leetcode.com/problems/basic-calculator/)

#### 1. Clarify
(1) Is the input "[abc]" a valid input? -No, if there is a [], there must be a number in front of it

#### 2. Idea
This is a DFS problem, for example s = "2[ab3[cd4[ef]]5[gh]]", the tree is
<img src="https://assets.leetcode.com/users/qy9mg/image_1584966338.png" width="300">
If a node is a number k, it means its children will be repeated k times. 
If a node is a string, it means you can use it directly. 
If two nodes are in the same level, that means we need to append the string represented by the next tree to the string represented by the previous tree, for example, string rooted at ab + string rooted at 3 + string rooted at 5

if dfs(node) returns the string rooted at node, we should define dfs(node) like this:
```
dfs(node){
	StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
	String children = dfs(child1) + dfs(child2) + dfs(child3) + ...
	for(int i = 0; i < node.k; i ++){
		sb.append(children);
	}
	return sb.toString();
}
```

#### 3. Solution
**Solution 1. Recursive** [This solution is from this post](https://leetcode.com/problems/decode-string/discuss/87544/Clean-C%2B%2B-Recursive-Solution-with-Explanation)
```
class Solution {

    private int idx;
    private String s;

    public String decodeString(String s) {
        idx = 0;
        this.s = s;
        return helper();
    }

    private String helper() {
        int num = 0;
        String word = "";
        for(; idx < s.length(); idx++) {
            char cur = s.charAt(idx);
            if(cur == '[') {
                idx ++;
                String curStr = helper();
                for(; num > 0; num--) word += curStr;
            }
            else if (cur >= '0' && cur <='9') {
                num = num * 10 + cur - '0';
            }
            else if (cur == ']') {
                return word;
            }
            else { 
                word += cur;
            }
        }
        return word;
    }
}
```

-----
**Solution 2 Interative**
Iterative solution explanation:
The way the operation system deals with recursion is, before enter the next level of the recursive method, push the current state into a stack; after the next level of recursive method is done, fetch the state before it's excuted, and do calcuation using the state and the result of the next level of recursive method, for example, the fibonacci series:

Before fibonacci(n - 2) runs, the OS must run fibonacci(n - 1)  and push its result into a stack, after fibonacci(n - 1) is run and get the result, the OS fetch the result of fibonacci(n - 2) and sum up with fibonacci(n - 1) and return.

```
int fibonacci(n){
	if(n == 1) return 1;
	if(n == 2) return 2;

	return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
}
```

In this problem, as is written in the top, we are using dfs to solve this problem:
```
dfs(node){
	StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(node.stringBeforeFirstChild);
	String children = dfs(node.child0) + dfs(node.child1) + dfs(node.child2) + ...
	for(int i = 0; i < node.k; i ++){
		sb.append(children);
	}

	sb.append(node.stringAfterLastChild);
	return sb.toString();
}
```

(1) When we encounter '[', it means we are going into the child, so we must push the current state into stacks. The current state includes the number k and the current String we get. Then we must reset the number and the current string because now we are processing the next level.
(2) when we encounter ']', it means we finish the current level, now we must fetch the state before we go into this level, append the current level's result after the previous state. 

```
class Solution {
    public String decodeString(String s){
        Stack<Integer> counts = new Stack<>();
        Stack<String> prefixes = new Stack<>();

        int count = 0;
        StringBuilder curString = new StringBuilder();

        for (char c: s.toCharArray()){
            if (Character.isDigit(c)){
                count = count * 10 + c - '0';
            }
            else if (Character.isLetter(c)){
                curString.append(c);
            }
            else if (c == '['){
                counts.add(count);
                prefixes.add(curString.toString());

                count = 0;
                curString = new StringBuilder();
            }
            else {
                String temp = curString.toString();
                curString = new StringBuilder(prefixes.pop());
                int repeatTimes = counts.pop();

                for(int i = 0; i < repeatTimes; i ++){
                    curString.append(temp);
                }
            }
        }
        return curString.toString();
    }
}
```

#### 4. Complexity
TC: Both solutions are O(n) where n is the length of the string
SC: solution 1 is O(1), solution 2 is O(n)

