First, we have to find an opening bracket from the end. This is due to the fact that the brackets can be stacked within each other. The right-most opening bracket is guaranteed to be the innermost one.

```c++
int first = s.rfind('[');
```

If no opening bracket exists, we can return the initial string, otherwise, we should find the matching closing bracket, which is guaranteed to be the one after the opening bracket.

```c++
if (first == string::npos) return s;
int second = s.find(']', first + 1);
```

After finding the brackets, we now have to find `k`, which is the amount of repetitions for the value inside the brackets. For this, we can search backward until we reach a non-digit, or the beginning of the string.

```c++
int kLength = 1;
for (;; ++kLength) {
	if (first - kLength < 0 || !isdigit(s[first - kLength])) {
		--kLength;
		break;
	}
}
```

After our search is complete, we can convert the found string to an integer using `stoi`.

```c++
int k = stoi(s.substr(first - kLength, kLength));
```

Now that we have the values for the `k` and the encoded string, we can split `s` into three parts: 
- Before `k` and the encoded string
- The encoded string repeated `k` times
- After `k` and the encoded string

To find the before and after strings, we can use

```c++
string before = s.substr(0, first - kLength);
string after = s.substr(second + 1);
```

To get the encoded string repeated `k` times, we can use

```c++
string decoded = "";
string substr = s.substr(first + 1, second - first - 1);
for (int i = 0; i < k; ++i) {
	decoded += substr;
}
```

and reconstruct `s` using

```c++
s = before + decoded + after;
```

We then will apply this operation recursively until no brackets remain, and return the `s` value.

```c++
return decodeString(s);
```

The overall code can be found below. Note that we are using the reference value of `s`, using `&` operator. This is due to the fact that we are changing the value of `s` in each iteration.

```c++
string decodeString(string& s) {
	int first = s.rfind('[');
	if (first == string::npos) return s;
	int second = s.find(']', first + 1);

	int kLength = 1;
	for (;; ++kLength) {
		if (first - kLength < 0 || !isdigit(s[first - kLength])) {
			--kLength;
			break;
		}
	}
	int k = stoi(s.substr(first - kLength, kLength));

	string before = s.substr(0, first - kLength);
	string after = s.substr(second + 1);

	string decoded = "";
	string substr = s.substr(first + 1, second - first - 1);
	for (int i = 0; i < k; ++i) {
		decoded += substr;
	}

	s = before + decoded + after;

	return decodeString(s);
}
```

