__Lets Take an example first and see its solution
s = 2[ab]2[d3[a2[c]]]__
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/047f146c-1938-4bec-9ca2-795e705d245c_1655635970.822745.jpeg)
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2d37b4f9-30e5-4c8c-8548-45d066c69a6a_1655635982.9163513.jpeg)
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/0b4c4ff3-82a1-4bd3-a616-3b37139c3199_1655635999.5368323.jpeg)
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/a772021a-67a0-4fab-bf0c-b04d6fc16f7c_1655636006.9801486.jpeg)


__So as per the images, arrows represent returning a control, therefore we will recursion to solve this problem.
The Idea is to add all the sets of independent brackets
For every call, our current result is an empty string, we advance in the string and perform the following tasks__
>__If the current character is an opening bracket, we hold our current result and recursively check for any nested brackets__
>>__To solve the current pair of brackets, we have to ensure all the brackets inside it are solved!!
>>After A recursive call is finished, we set the multiplier (integer that tells us how many times our string will be repeated) to 0
>>We take the control to the next index which has to been traversed yet,__
>>>__Take an array and initialise all values to 0
>>>Whenever an index is encountered, set it to 1 in the array.
>>>0 ---> Untraversed, 1 ---> Traversed
>>>Therefore we take the control to the next index with value 0__
>>>
>__If current character is a letter, we add it to our current result and continue to advance  in the input string
>If the current character is an closing bracket,__
>> __We repeat our current result, multiplier times, and store it in a temporary string
>> We return the temporary string, this operation ends one set of brackets__
>> 
>__Otherwise the current character is a digit,__ 
>> __It will give us the multiplier, so we will store it in another variable
>> This will help us to pass on the multiplier to another recursive call, if needed, after converting it into integer__
>> 
__Finally we will return the Current Result__
____
__Below is the C++ code for the above mentioned approach__


```
class Solution
{ // Runtime: 0 ms, faster than 100.00% of C++ online submissions for Decode String.
  // Memory Usage: 6.4 MB, less than 78.36% of C++ online submissions for Decode String.
public:
    int l, br = 0;
    // Since string length can at worst be 30, create an array of length 30 to track the indices that have been traversed
    int v[30]; 

    string get_it(string s, int index, int mul) //(Original String, index to start with, multiplier)
    {
        //Res to store immidiate results, 
        //result_so_far to get the result so far, 
        //num to get the multiplier
        string res = "", result_so_far = "", num = "";       
        int b = 0, i = index;
        while(i < l)
        {
            //Mark the index as traversed
            v[i] = 1;
            //If there is an opening
            if (s[i] == '[')                        
            {
                //For Every beginning, make a recursive call, as there might be nested Coded Strings like 3[a2[c]]
                //Store the result of the recursive call in result_so_far
                result_so_far += get_it(s, i + 1, stoi(num));
                //Set num as "", empty!
                num = "";
                //Take i to the next untraversed index
                while (v[i] != 0)
                    i++;
            }
            //If there is an alphabet, add it to result_so_far
            else if (isalpha(s[i]))
            {
                result_so_far += s[i++];
            }
            //If its a closing bracket
            else if (s[i] == ']')
            {
                //Time to add the strings, m times,
                //This step is responsible for decoding(building up) the string
                for (int i = 1; i <= mul; i++)
                    res += result_so_far;       //Immediate immresult
                return res;
            }
            //Otherwise the current character is a part of multiplier, i.e. number
            else
                num += s[i++];
        }   
        return result_so_far;
    }
    string decodeString(string s)
    {
        l = s.size();
        //Set the l(size) places in the array v, as 0, stating all are untraversed
        for (int i = 0; i < l; i++)  
            v[i] = 0;

        return get_it(s, 0, 1);
    }
};
```
__Time Complexity : O(N), N = Length of the String
Space Complexity : O(N), Since recursion uses a stack to process the info__

