# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
-Traverse the string from start to finish and while doing so,
--Use charS stack To store all the characters except for ']'
--Use numS stack To store all the numbers
--Once we hit a char == ']' we pop from charS until we get '[', and then we pop once from numS to get the number of repetitions. 
-- construct the new string and push it back on to the charS stack and continue the loop.

(Let me know if you need any clarification)

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: 
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public String decodeString(String s) {
        Stack<Integer> numS = new Stack();
        Stack<String> charS = new Stack();

        for(int i = 0;i<s.length();i++){
            if(s.charAt(i) == ']'){
                int k = numS.pop();

                String ch = charS.pop();
                String toConcat = "";
                while(!ch.equals("[")){
                    toConcat = ch+toConcat;
                    ch = charS.pop(); 
                }
                String concat = "";
                while(k>0){
                    concat = concat + toConcat;
                    k--;
                }
                charS.push(concat);

            }else if(Character.isDigit(s.charAt(i))){
                numS.push(Integer.valueOf(s.substring(i,s.indexOf('[',i))));
                i = s.indexOf('[',i)-1;
            }else{
                charS.push(Character.toString(s.charAt(i)));
            }

        }

        String result="";
         while(!charS.empty()){
            result = charS.pop() + result;
         }
        return result;
    }
}
